<pb facs="hta.009.001"/>
    
    <head>LECTURE V.</head>
    <head type="sub">GENESIS, VIII. PART OF VER. 1. <lb/>
    <hi rend="italic">And God remembered Noah.</hi></head>

    <p>And God, my beloved friends, will never forget nor desert those who remember his law, and act with reference to his commandment. Be assured, that although the Lord may not now-a-days appear to work miracles in our eyes, he does nevertheless extend a special protection over the righteous. He ordereth all things for their good; and he taketh them out of the great waterfloods of affliction, if they really cast their care on him. He who worked the greater deliverance of Noah,&#8212;he who baptized the whole earth, and made it a type of that regeneration which was afterwards to be received by the elect people of God&#8212;he can always effect the lesser deliverance of individuals. And, probably, he would be much more ready to help us, if we had faith but as a grain of mustard-seed, and were not so troubled, as we are, about many things. Why are we so dull of understanding, so slow to remember that the very hairs of our head are numbered, and that a sparrow does
    
<pb facs="hta.009.002"/>    
    not fall to the ground unnoticed? Amongst other salutary effects attending on a frequent perusal of the Scriptures, it will not be a small thing that we accustom ourselves to consider God as always actually present, directing every dispensation which we call nature, regulating the seasons, pouring forth his rain, diffusing his sunshine, and spreading his hoar frost like ashes; frowning on us in every tempest, sending forth his ministers of wrath in the forms of war, pestilence, and famine, to fulfil his word; and sometimes, how much oftener than we deserve, intimating, by intervals of tranquillity, health, and abundance, what should be our lot did we always turn unto him; what shall be our lot when Christ restores the kingdom to his saints. It is good, therefore, for us continually to meditate on those periods of the world, when God spake with man face to face, or at least by some unequivocal voice or vision.</p>
    <p>"And God remembered Noah."&#8212;The details of the deluge have been recorded with singular minuteness. Let us recall to our memories the principal circumstances, in their natural series.&#8212;The rain was upon the earth forty days and forty night: during the period of forty days, it ceased not to rain; and, probably, during the same time, all the subterraneous resources of moisture were in
    
<pb facs="hta.009.003"/>
    a constant state of activity, so that the flood was uniformly accumulating in depth, and all things beneath its surface were in a state of flux and confusion. No doubt the work of vengeance and desturction went on during these forty days. They may be considered as teh appointed time of purification; so that there should afterwards be, as it were, a new earth, and, in some respects, a new heaven: I speak of the atmosphere and its ordinary characteristics. We may, without any charge of superstition, be allowed to remark, that God set apart the same precise number of days for thus washing away the antediluvian offences, as he enjoyed Moses to await in Mount Sinai, before he was deemed fit to recieve the communications fo the Spirit: and that in this latter instance there was something very perculiar intended by the term of forty days, we are sure, because when Moses, having, in his zealous indignation against idolatry, broken the first tables, was allowed to receive them a second time secluded in the mountain forty days, as before, previous to the renewal of the law. Including the above forty days of rain, the waters prevailed on the earth one hundred and fifty days. During this time we are not to supposed that there was neither increase nor decrease: the waters had exceeded the summits of the loftiest mountains by fifteen cuits; of
    
<pb facs="hta.009.004"/>    
    course they covered the ordinary level of the earth by many hundred feet. This alone proves that the accumulation far exceeded what could have been prodcued by even forty days of incessant rain under usual circumstances: it proves that the fountains of the deep were broken up, and that hte element had "a message from the Lord." Such an amazing body of water though gradually subsiding, was said to prevail on the earth one hundred and fifty days, because, until the expiration of that time, no sensible proof was adduced of its diminution. At the end of one hundred and fifty days, i.e. five months from the commencement of the rain, did the ark rest upon the mountains of Ararat in Armenia. Though the waters decreased continually, yet it was not until other forty days had elapsed from the time of the ark becoming thus stationary, that even the tops of mountains were seen. The rapidity with which earth, and all its tenants, all its productions, all its original beauties, had sunk beneath the avenging waters, when compared with the slowness, the tediousness, and, as it were, the reluctance of its recovery, was doubtless meant to impress on the mind of Noah and his family, as it must impresss on the mind of every reflecting person, this lesson: the desolation which human profligacy, both individual and national, pours out like a flood, constantly leaves behind it effects
    
<pb facs="hta.009.005"/>    
    which many succeeding generations must deplore, and of which no lapse of time can quite eradicate the deepended vestiges.</p>
    




